        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "If your blog was selected, you have earned Stacc's recognition as one of the 100 best SEO and marketing blogs of 2026.\n\nDisplay your award on your site. Email hello@thestacc.com with the subject line \"Best SEO Blogs Badge\" and we will send you a badge image and embed code. Display it on your site to show your readers you made the list. And link back to this page.\n\n\nFive blogs have earned the distinction of shaping how the entire SEO industry thinks. They do not follow trends. They set them. Each publishes original research, data studies, and frameworks that every other blog on this list cites. If you read nothing else here, read these.\nAhrefs Blog. Ahrefs\nNo SEO blog is cited more often than Ahrefs. Their original research. Drawn from a live index of billions of web pages. Produces studies the entire industry builds on. Tim Soulo and the team turn raw data into strategies anyone can apply immediately. When Ahrefs publishes, it becomes the benchmark for everyone else. Start here for keyword research grounded in real data.\n\nWebsite: ahrefs.com/blog\nX/Twitter: @ahrefs\nLinkedIn: Ahrefs\nPublishing Frequency: 3 to 5 times per week\nBest for: Data-driven SEO strategies and original research studies\n\nSemrush Blog. Semrush\nSemrush has become the single largest marketing knowledge hub on the internet. After acquiring Search Engine Land and Backlinko, their blog now covers every corner of digital marketing at a depth no single publisher could match. For teams that need one trusted source across SEO, PPC, and content strategy, there is nothing more complete.\n\nWebsite: semrush.com/blog\nX/Twitter: @semrush\nLinkedIn: Semrush\nPublishing Frequency: Daily\nBest for: All-in-one marketing guides across SEO, PPC, and content\n\nMoz Blog. Moz\nMoz built the SEO community that educated an entire generation of practitioners. With over 500,000 members, their blog has been the entry point for countless SEO careers. Whiteboard Friday. One of the longest-running SEO video series. Breaks down complex ranking topics in ten clear minutes. Their beginner guides on on-page SEO remain essential reading two decades later.\n\nWebsite: moz.com/blog\nX/Twitter: @Moz\nLinkedIn: Moz\nPublishing Frequency: 3 to 4 times per week\nBest for: Community-driven SEO education and Whiteboard Friday videos\n\nBacklinko. Brian Dean / Semrush\nBrian Dean built Backlinko on a principle few blogs follow: publish less, but make every post exceptional. Each article runs 3,000 to 5,000 words with frameworks that practitioners actually use. Now under Semrush ownership, Backlinko remains the most referenced source for link building strategy and long-form content. Few blogs have influenced how the industry writes content as much as this one.\n\nWebsite: backlinko.com\nX/Twitter: @backlinko\nLinkedIn: Backlinko\nPublishing Frequency: 2 to 3 times per month\nBest for: Deep, actionable long-form guides on link building and content\n\nNeil Patel Blog. Neil Patel\nNeil Patel reaches over 4 million monthly readers. One of the largest audiences in digital marketing. His blog pairs free tools like Ubersuggest with step-by-step tutorials that cover everything from technical SEO to conversion optimization. For beginners who want results without a budget, Neil's combination of free software and plain-language teaching is unmatched. See also our guide on how to rank higher on Google.\n\nWebsite: neilpatel.com/blog\nX/Twitter: @neilpatel\nLinkedIn: Neil Patel\nPublishing Frequency: Daily\nBest for: SEO beginners who want free tools paired with tutorials\n\n\nThese blogs have earned recognition for keeping the SEO community informed in real time. When Google ships a core update, these are the sources professionals open first. They report on changes within hours, often before Google confirms them publicly. Follow at least one to stay ahead of your competitors.\nSearch Engine Roundtable. Barry Schwartz\nBarry Schwartz has been the SEO community's fastest news source for over 20 years. He monitors WebmasterWorld forums and X/Twitter to catch ranking shifts before Google confirms them. Sometimes publishing multiple updates per day during active algorithm periods. When something moves in search, Barry reports it first. Bookmark this site and check it after every unexplained traffic drop.\n\nWebsite: seroundtable.com\nX/Twitter: @seroundtable\nLinkedIn: Barry Schwartz\nPublishing Frequency: Multiple times daily\nBest for: Breaking SEO news and algorithm change tracking\n\nSearch Engine Land. Semrush / Third Door Media\nSearch Engine Land has set the standard for search industry journalism since 2006. Now under Semrush ownership after the 2024 Third Door Media acquisition, it pairs breaking news with editorial analysis that tells you when to act on an update and when to wait. Danny Goodwin and the team provide the context that raw news sources cannot.\n\nWebsite: searchengineland.com\nX/Twitter: @sengineland\nLinkedIn: Search Engine Land\nPublishing Frequency: Daily\nBest for: Expert editorial analysis of search industry changes\n\nSearch Engine Journal. Loren Baker\nSearch Engine Journal has assembled one of the largest contributor networks in search marketing. With 10+ articles per day from working practitioners. Not just journalists. SEJ delivers diverse perspectives on E-E-A-T, algorithm changes, PPC, and content strategy. Few publications offer the breadth of expert voices that SEJ does.\n\nWebsite: searchenginejournal.com\nX/Twitter: @sejournal\nLinkedIn: Search Engine Journal\nPublishing Frequency: 10+ articles daily\nBest for: Multi-author coverage across all search marketing topics\n\nGoogle Search Central Blog. Google\nThis is the only blog on this list that speaks with absolute authority on search. Every other publication interprets what Google publishes here. When Google documents a core update, structured data change, or crawling behavior, it appears here first. Every SEO professional owes it to their work to monitor this blog directly.\n\nWebsite: developers.google.com/search/blog\nX/Twitter: @googlesearchc\nLinkedIn: Google\nPublishing Frequency: 2 to 4 times per month\nBest for: Official Google announcements and documentation\n\n\nWant results without reading 65 blogs every week? Stacc publishes 30 SEO-optimized articles per month for your business. Zero effort on your end.\nStart for $1 --&gt;\n\n\nTechnical SEO is the foundation every other ranking factor depends on. These blogs have been recognized for their depth on crawlability, indexing, site speed, and structured data. They cover problems that general SEO blogs never surface. And solutions that move the needle on large sites.\nScreaming Frog Blog. Screaming Frog\nThe team behind the most widely used desktop crawler has produced some of the most thorough technical SEO documentation available. Their guides on log file analysis, crawl budgets, and site migrations go far beyond product tutorials. They are practical references for any technical SEO facing complex audit challenges. Essential reading before and after every site migration.\n\nWebsite: screamingfrog.co.uk/blog\nX/Twitter: @screamingfrog\nLinkedIn: Screaming Frog\nPublishing Frequency: 2 to 3 times per month\nBest for: Crawl audits, site migrations, and technical SEO tutorials\n\nBotify Blog. Botify\nBotify earned its reputation by solving crawl problems that most tools cannot even surface. Their blog covers crawl budget management, JavaScript rendering, and log file analysis at a scale that enterprise teams actually face. The insights here come from working with sites that have millions of indexed pages. A level of technical depth you will not find on general SEO blogs.\n\nWebsite: botify.com/blog\nX/Twitter: @botify\nLinkedIn: Botify\nPublishing Frequency: Weekly\nBest for: Enterprise technical SEO and crawl budget optimization\n\nLumar Blog. Lumar (formerly Deepcrawl)\nLumar has built a strong reputation for technical SEO research that goes beyond surface-level audits. Their work on JavaScript SEO, Core Web Vitals, and site architecture is backed by real crawl data from mid-to-large websites. For technical teams that need guidance on indexation and internal linking at scale, Lumar's blog is a consistent and reliable resource.\n\nWebsite: lumar.io/blog\nX/Twitter: @LumarIO\nLinkedIn: Lumar\nPublishing Frequency: Weekly\nBest for: Site architecture, internal linking, and JavaScript SEO\n\nContentKing Blog. ContentKing (now part of Conductor)\nContentKing has pioneered the case for real-time SEO monitoring, and their blog reflects that forward-thinking approach. Rather than waiting for weekly crawls to surface issues, their guides teach proactive on-page monitoring, indexation change detection, and audit strategies that catch problems before rankings drop. An important voice for teams that cannot afford SEO surprises.\n\nWebsite: contentkingapp.com/blog\nX/Twitter: @ContentKingApp\nLinkedIn: ContentKing\nPublishing Frequency: 2 to 3 times per month\nBest for: Real-time SEO monitoring and on-page change detection\n\nSearchPilot Blog. SearchPilot\nSearchPilot occupies a position no other blog holds: they run controlled SEO A/B tests on major websites and publish exactly what happened to traffic. No speculation. No opinion. When they test a title tag change or schema addition, they show the actual impact numbers. For practitioners who need evidence-backed decisions, SearchPilot's case studies are the closest thing to a laboratory in SEO.\n\nWebsite: searchpilot.com/blog\nX/Twitter: @SearchPilot\nLinkedIn: SearchPilot\nPublishing Frequency: Monthly\nBest for: SEO A/B testing case studies with real traffic data\n\nZyppy Blog. Cyrus Shepard\nCyrus Shepard has produced some of the most-cited title tag research in the SEO industry. A former Moz contributor, he now runs Zyppy and publishes focused, data-driven work on click-through rates and SERP features. His studies on title tag truncation and CTR impact have shaped how practitioners write page titles. A specialist resource that rewards careful reading.\n\nWebsite: zyppy.com/blog\nX/Twitter: @CyrusShepard\nLinkedIn: Cyrus Shepard\nPublishing Frequency: 1 to 2 times per month\nBest for: Title tag optimization and CTR research\n\n\nLocal search has its own rulebook, and these blogs have earned recognition as the definitive sources for navigating it. Google Business Profile updates, local pack algorithms, and citation strategies require specialized knowledge that general SEO blogs never develop. These four publications have built that expertise over years of focused work.\nBrightLocal Blog. BrightLocal\nBrightLocal has produced the most trusted annual local SEO research in the industry for over a decade. Their \"State of Local SEO\" report sets benchmarks used by agencies worldwide, and their studies on review signals and citation impact remain the most referenced in the field. If you manage Google Business Profiles, this blog is not optional reading. It is required. See also our local SEO guide.\n\nWebsite: brightlocal.com/blog\nX/Twitter: @BrightLocal\nLinkedIn: BrightLocal\nPublishing Frequency: 3 to 4 times per week\nBest for: Local SEO research, citation strategies, and GBP management\n\nWhitespark Blog. Darren Shaw\nDarren Shaw and the Whitespark team have become the definitive authority on local citations and GBP optimization. Their annual \"Local Search Ranking Factors\" survey is the most widely referenced benchmark in local SEO. Every post delivers the kind of depth that comes from practitioners who work with local search daily. For citation strategy and GBP work, there is no more credible source.\n\nWebsite: whitespark.ca/blog\nX/Twitter: @DarrenShaw_\nLinkedIn: Darren Shaw\nPublishing Frequency: 2 to 3 times per month\nBest for: Citation building, local link building, and GBP optimization\n\nSterling Sky Blog. Joy Hawkins\nJoy Hawkins is a Google Business Profile Top Contributor, and Sterling Sky reflects that insider access. Their blog covers GBP bugs, local algorithm shifts, and Map Pack ranking strategies that no other publication tracks with the same consistency. When the local algorithm moves in unexpected ways, Sterling Sky is almost always the first to document it. Follow this blog to catch local changes before your competitors do.\n\nWebsite: sterlingsky.ca/blog\nX/Twitter: @JoyanneHawkins\nLinkedIn: Joy Hawkins\nPublishing Frequency: 2 to 4 times per month\nBest for: GBP bugs, local algorithm updates, and Map Pack strategies\n\nLocalU Blog. LocalU\nLocalU has been the education hub for local SEO practitioners since the field was still finding its footing. Their blog brings together expert roundups, ranking factor analysis, and GBP guidance from the practitioners who train other professionals. For agency teams managing multiple locations, LocalU provides the structured knowledge base that makes multi-location SEO manageable.\n\nWebsite: localu.org/blog\nX/Twitter: @LocalU\nLinkedIn: LocalU\nPublishing Frequency: Monthly\nBest for: Local SEO training resources and expert roundups\n\n\nLocal SEO is hard to do alone. Stacc writes location-specific content for service businesses, auto-published to your site every week.\nStart for $1 --&gt;\n\n\nGreat content is what makes every other SEO strategy work. These blogs have earned recognition for their depth on content marketing strategy, editorial operations, and the writing craft that turns organic traffic into actual business results.\nHubSpot Blog. HubSpot\nHubSpot runs the largest marketing blog on the internet, and the scale of their data access shows. Drawing insights from millions of customers across email, SEO, sales, and CRM, their \"State of Marketing\" report sets annual benchmarks the entire industry references. For content teams that need reliable data to back their strategies, HubSpot is the source that never runs dry.\n\nWebsite: blog.hubspot.com\nX/Twitter: @HubSpot\nLinkedIn: HubSpot\nPublishing Frequency: Daily\nBest for: Content calendar planning, distribution strategies, and marketing benchmarks\n\nContent Marketing Institute. Joe Pulizzi / CMI\nJoe Pulizzi built the Content Marketing Institute from the ground up, and it remains the gold standard for B2B content education. CMI publishes research, case studies, and editorial workflow frameworks used by marketing teams at the world's largest companies. As content marketing has matured into a discipline, CMI has been the institution that gave it structure.\n\nWebsite: contentmarketinginstitute.com\nX/Twitter: @CMIContent\nLinkedIn: Joe Pulizzi\nPublishing Frequency: Daily\nBest for: B2B content strategy, editorial workflows, and research reports\n\nCopyBlogger. Brian Clark\nBrian Clark launched CopyBlogger in 2006 and created one of the most influential blogs in the history of content marketing. The focus on copywriting craft, narrative structure, and conversion-focused writing has shaped how an entire generation approaches SEO content. Nearly two decades later, CopyBlogger continues to publish with the same dedication to the written word that built its reputation.\n\nWebsite: copyblogger.com\nX/Twitter: @copyblogger\nLinkedIn: Brian Clark\nPublishing Frequency: 2 to 3 times per week\nBest for: Copywriting fundamentals, storytelling, and persuasion techniques\n\nAnimalz Blog. Animalz\nAnimalz has earned recognition as one of the most intellectually rigorous content marketing agencies in the SaaS space. Their blog is the byproduct of doing the work at a high level. Every post on content strategy, editorial operations, and content-led growth reflects real client experience. Jimmy Daly and team publish at a level of sharpness that most agency blogs do not come close to matching.\n\nWebsite: animalz.co/blog\nX/Twitter: @AnimalzCo\nLinkedIn: Animalz\nPublishing Frequency: Weekly\nBest for: SaaS content strategy and content-led growth frameworks\n\nSuperpath Blog. Jimmy Daly\nJimmy Daly built Superpath into the most useful community for serious content marketers. The blog tackles the operational realities that most content publications ignore: hiring writers, building editorial processes, and scaling teams without sacrificing quality. For content leaders at growing companies, Superpath answers the questions that generic marketing blogs never ask.\n\nWebsite: superpath.co/blog\nX/Twitter: @Superpath_\nLinkedIn: Jimmy Daly\nPublishing Frequency: Weekly\nBest for: Content operations, editorial team building, and career growth\n\nOrbit Media Blog. Andy Crestodina\nAndy Crestodina has produced some of the most reliably useful original research in content marketing. His annual \"Blogger Survey\". Tracking how bloggers work, what drives results, and where the industry is heading. Is cited across publications every year. Every Orbit Media post pairs data with steps you can implement the same day. Consistency at this level over many years is genuinely rare.\n\nWebsite: orbitmedia.com/blog\nX/Twitter: @orbiteers\nLinkedIn: Andy Crestodina\nPublishing Frequency: Weekly\nBest for: Blogging research, content strategy, and web design for marketers\n\nBuffer Blog. Buffer\nBuffer has earned recognition for publishing some of the most honest, data-backed social media research available. Rather than promoting unrealistic tactics, their guides on publishing frequency, content formats, and engagement are drawn from their own platform data. For content teams that distribute across social alongside SEO, Buffer's blog provides the strategic grounding to do it right.\n\nWebsite: buffer.com/resources\nX/Twitter: @buffer\nLinkedIn: Buffer\nPublishing Frequency: 3 to 4 times per week\nBest for: Social media distribution and content scheduling strategies\n\nHootsuite Blog. Hootsuite\nHootsuite has established itself as the benchmark publisher for enterprise social media intelligence. Their annual \"Social Trends\" report is one of the most widely cited documents in the industry, drawing data from millions of social profiles. For marketers who manage social channels alongside SEO and content operations, Hootsuite's blog gives the strategic context that platform-specific guides cannot.\n\nWebsite: blog.hootsuite.com\nX/Twitter: @hootsuite\nLinkedIn: Hootsuite\nPublishing Frequency: Daily\nBest for: Social media trends, analytics, and enterprise social management\n\n\nBacklinks still determine rankings in 2026. These blogs focus on outreach, digital PR, and earning links at scale. And they have been recognized for doing it honestly, with real data behind their methods. Read them alongside our link building strategies guide.\nFat Joe Blog. Fat Joe\nFat Joe has built one of the most transparent link building resources in the industry. Their \"State of Link Building\" reports include real pricing data from thousands of campaigns. The kind of market intelligence that agencies and in-house teams rarely access. For practitioners who want honest guidance on outreach, guest posting, and link prospecting, Fat Joe delivers without inflated claims.\n\nWebsite: fatjoe.com/blog\nX/Twitter: @fatjoeblog\nLinkedIn: Fat Joe\nPublishing Frequency: Weekly\nBest for: Link building pricing data, outreach templates, and guest posting\n\nPage One Power Blog. Page One Power\nPage One Power has built a reputation for doing link building the right way and documenting it openly. Their transparent case studies cover manual outreach campaigns, relationship-based link acquisition, and the nuanced criteria behind link quality assessment. For practitioners committed to white-hat strategies, Page One Power's blog is the most honest account of what real link building looks like.\n\nWebsite: pageonepower.com/blog\nX/Twitter: @PageOnePower\nLinkedIn: Page One Power\nPublishing Frequency: 2 to 3 times per month\nBest for: White-hat link building case studies and outreach strategies\n\nSiege Media Blog. Siege Media\nSiege Media has made content-driven link building a discipline, and their blog is the proof. Case studies published on their site include actual traffic numbers and link counts. Not vague success stories. For teams that want to earn links through content rather than outreach volume, Siege Media shows exactly how that is done at scale and at a sustainable pace.\n\nWebsite: siegemedia.com/blog\nX/Twitter: @siegemedia\nLinkedIn: Siege Media\nPublishing Frequency: Weekly\nBest for: Content-driven link building and digital PR campaigns\n\nDigitaloft Blog. Digitaloft\nDigitaloft has earned its place as a leading voice on data-driven digital PR in the UK market and beyond. Their blog documents how newsworthy content campaigns earn editorial links from publications that would never accept a cold pitch. Their work on newsjacking and reactive PR shows a methodology that turns topical moments into lasting backlinks.\n\nWebsite: digitaloft.co.uk/blog\nX/Twitter: @digitaloft\nLinkedIn: Digitaloft\nPublishing Frequency: 2 to 3 times per month\nBest for: Digital PR campaigns and earning links from news publications\n\n\nLink building takes months of outreach. Stacc publishes content that earns links naturally. 30 articles per month, zero outreach required.\nStart for $1 --&gt;\n\n\nThese blogs have been recognized for testing SEO tools hands-on and publishing honest comparisons. They go further than vendor blogs with independent testing, real cost data, and opinions that are not shaped by marketing budgets. Read them before buying any SEO software. See also our list of best free SEO tools.\nAuthority Hacker. Gael Breton and Mark Webster\nGael Breton and Mark Webster built over $10 million in authority site revenue before publishing any advice on how to do it. That foundation makes Authority Hacker's tool reviews unlike anything else. Assessments built on actual portfolio data, not affiliate incentives. Their roundups are blunt about what does not work and specific about what does. A rare standard in an industry full of unqualified opinions.\n\nWebsite: authorityhacker.com\nX/Twitter: @authorityhacker\nLinkedIn: Gael Breton\nPublishing Frequency: Weekly\nBest for: Honest SEO tool reviews based on real site portfolio data\n\nNiche Pursuits. Spencer Haws\nSpencer Haws has reviewed more SEO tools than almost any other independent publisher, and he does it through the practical lens of someone actively building niche sites. With over 2,400 published articles, Niche Pursuits is one of the most complete independent SEO tool databases available. For bloggers and site builders comparing affordable platforms, Spencer's real-world testing is the gold standard.\n\nWebsite: nichepursuits.com\nX/Twitter: @NichePursuits\nLinkedIn: Spencer Haws\nPublishing Frequency: 3 to 5 times per week\nBest for: Niche site building strategies and SEO tool comparisons\n\nBlogging Wizard. Adam Connell\nAdam Connell has built one of the most complete independent review libraries in the blogging and content tool space. His detailed assessments are regularly updated with current pricing and feature changes. Not left to go stale after the initial publish date. For writers and content teams comparing tools for blog production and optimization, Blogging Wizard saves hours of independent research.\n\nWebsite: bloggingwizard.com\nX/Twitter: @adamjayc\nLinkedIn: Adam Connell\nPublishing Frequency: 3 to 4 times per week\nBest for: Detailed SEO and blogging tool roundups with pricing data\n\nSE Ranking Blog. SE Ranking\nSE Ranking has produced a consistently strong blog that stands apart from most vendor publications. Rather than limiting content to product tutorials, they publish industry studies and educational guides useful regardless of which tools you use. For mid-market SEO teams that need reliable guidance on rank tracking and site auditing, SE Ranking's blog delivers genuine depth.\n\nWebsite: seranking.com/blog\nX/Twitter: @SERanking\nLinkedIn: SE Ranking\nPublishing Frequency: 3 to 4 times per week\nBest for: Rank tracking tutorials and mid-market SEO tool education\n\nMangools Blog. Mangools\nMangools has built a blog that serves its audience. Solopreneurs and small teams. With exactly the right level of depth. Their keyword research guides and SERP analysis tutorials explain concepts clearly without assuming enterprise budgets or advanced technical knowledge. For practitioners getting started with affordable tools, Mangools sets the bar for accessible, honest SEO education.\n\nWebsite: mangools.com/blog\nX/Twitter: @mangools_com\nLinkedIn: Mangools\nPublishing Frequency: Weekly\nBest for: Beginner keyword research guides and affordable tool tutorials\n\nSurfer SEO Blog. Surfer\nSurfer SEO has led the conversation on data-driven on-page optimization, and their blog reflects that expertise. Their guides on NLP-based content scoring, SERP competitive analysis, and content structure go beyond generic advice into the measurable signals that correlate with ranking improvements. For content teams that treat on-page SEO as a science rather than guesswork, Surfer's blog is essential.\n\nWebsite: surferseo.com/blog\nX/Twitter: @SurferSEO\nLinkedIn: Surfer SEO\nPublishing Frequency: Weekly\nBest for: Content optimization scores and on-page ranking strategies\n\n\nWordPress powers over 40% of the web, and the blogs in this category have earned recognition for making that platform's SEO complexity manageable. Whether you are configuring a plugin for the first time or debugging a complex schema implementation, these are the sources practitioners trust.\nYoast SEO Blog. Yoast\nThe team behind the most-installed WordPress SEO plugin has produced some of the clearest introductory SEO content on the internet. Yoast's blog sets a high bar for accessibility. Their guides on title tags, meta descriptions, and readability explain the fundamentals in plain language that beginners can actually act on. For anyone starting their WordPress SEO journey, this is the first blog to read alongside our SEO for beginners guide.\n\nWebsite: yoast.com/seo-blog\nX/Twitter: @yoast\nLinkedIn: Yoast\nPublishing Frequency: 3 to 4 times per week\nBest for: WordPress SEO plugin tutorials and beginner-friendly guides\n\nWPBeginner. Syed Balkhi\nSyed Balkhi built the definitive resource for WordPress users, and WPBeginner delivers on that promise every day. With a library covering every major SEO plugin, theme, and tool in the WordPress ecosystem, it is the first stop for site owners navigating a complex platform. When something changes in WordPress or its SEO toolset, WPBeginner documents it clearly and quickly.\n\nWebsite: wpbeginner.com\nX/Twitter: @wpbeginner\nLinkedIn: Syed Balkhi\nPublishing Frequency: Daily\nBest for: WordPress SEO plugins, themes, and hosting reviews\n\nRank Math Blog. Rank Math\nRank Math has become the fastest-growing SEO plugin in the WordPress ecosystem, and their blog shows why users trust the team behind it. Detailed tutorials on schema markup, redirects, and on-page optimization go well beyond product documentation into genuinely useful guides for any WordPress site owner. For practitioners who want structured data implemented correctly, Rank Math's schema resources are among the best available.\n\nWebsite: rankmath.com/blog\nX/Twitter: @RankMathSEO\nLinkedIn: Rank Math\nPublishing Frequency: 2 to 3 times per week\nBest for: WordPress schema markup and plugin-specific SEO tutorials\n\n\nOnline stores face unique SEO challenges that general blogs never cover: product pages, faceted navigation, structured data for reviews. These blogs have been recognized for developing genuine expertise in eCommerce-specific optimization. Not repurposed B2B advice.\nShopify Blog (SEO Section). Shopify\nShopify has invested heavily in SEO education for its merchant community, and the results speak for themselves. Their guides cover product page optimization, collection page structure, and platform-specific technical fixes that only Shopify practitioners face. For any merchant running a store on Shopify, this blog provides the most platform-accurate SEO guidance available. Written by the people who built the platform.\n\nWebsite: shopify.com/blog/topics/seo\nX/Twitter: @Shopify\nLinkedIn: Shopify\nPublishing Frequency: 2 to 3 times per week\nBest for: Shopify-specific SEO tutorials and product page optimization\n\nBigCommerce Blog. BigCommerce\nBigCommerce has produced a blog that serves mid-market eCommerce teams with the practical depth they need. Coverage spans SEO, email marketing, and conversion optimization with a level of specificity that platform-agnostic marketing blogs cannot match. For merchants evaluating platforms or managing stores at scale, BigCommerce's blog provides honest and well-informed guidance.\n\nWebsite: bigcommerce.com/blog\nX/Twitter: @BigCommerce\nLinkedIn: BigCommerce\nPublishing Frequency: 3 to 4 times per week\nBest for: Mid-market eCommerce SEO and platform migration guides\n\nMageworx Blog. Mageworx\nMageworx occupies a specialized position. Magento SEO. And they cover it with genuine expertise. Their blog addresses the real challenges Magento merchants face: product schema implementation, faceted navigation optimization, and platform-specific technical issues that generic eCommerce guides never reach. For anyone running a Magento store and taking SEO seriously, Mageworx is an indispensable resource.\n\nWebsite: mageworx.com/blog\nX/Twitter: @MageWorx\nLinkedIn: Mageworx\nPublishing Frequency: 2 to 3 times per month\nBest for: Magento SEO extensions and eCommerce structured data\n\n\nRunning an online store is hard enough. Stacc writes product descriptions, category pages, and blog content for eCommerce brands. Auto-published weekly.\nStart for $1 --&gt;\n\n\nThese blogs are run by working SEOs sharing tactics from active client campaigns. They have been recognized for one quality above all others: they show their work. Real data, real results, real mistakes. More tactical and more honest than the tool vendor blogs in the sections above.\nGotch SEO Blog. Nathan Gotch\nNathan Gotch has built one of the most operationally detailed SEO blogs for freelancers and small agencies. His step-by-step process documentation. Complete with screen recordings for audits, link building, and content optimization. Gives practitioners a replicable system rather than abstract theory. For SEO professionals who need to deliver consistent client results, Gotch SEO is the playbook.\n\nWebsite: gotchseo.com/blog\nX/Twitter: @nathangotch\nLinkedIn: Nathan Gotch\nPublishing Frequency: Weekly\nBest for: Step-by-step SEO processes for freelancers and agencies\n\nDiggity Marketing Blog. Matt Diggity\nMatt Diggity treats SEO like a laboratory, running controlled tests across his affiliate site network and publishing the results openly. His data on ranking factors, link building impact, and on-page changes comes from real experiments on real sites. Not hypotheses. For practitioners who need evidence to challenge conventional wisdom, Diggity Marketing delivers the most honest experimental data in the field.\n\nWebsite: diggitymarketing.com/blog\nX/Twitter: @MattDiggityAM\nLinkedIn: Matt Diggity\nPublishing Frequency: 2 to 3 times per month\nBest for: SEO split tests and controlled ranking experiments\n\nDetailed.com. Glen Allsopp\nGlen Allsopp produces a category of SEO research that no one else publishes. His deep investigations into who actually controls Google's search results. Uncovering hidden site networks, brand monopolies in SERPs, and the real competitive landscape. Have sparked industry-wide conversations. There is no other blog that looks at search results with the same forensic curiosity. Essential reading for anyone who wants to understand the game beyond the surface.\n\nWebsite: detailed.com\nX/Twitter: @ViperChill\nPublishing Frequency: 1 to 2 times per month\nBest for: SERP ownership research and competitive analysis\n\nSEO Notebook. Steve Toth\nSteve Toth's blog stands out for its specificity. Every post covers tactics he applies on active 